We use the trigonometric substitution

\begin{align*}x = 4\tan\theta, \quad dx = 4\sec^2\theta\,d\theta\end{align*}

and obtain

\begin{align*} \int \frac{dx}{\sqrt{x^2+16}} &= \int \frac{4\sec^2\theta\,d\theta}{\sqrt{16\tan^2\theta+16}} \\
&= \int \frac{4\sec^2\theta\,d\theta}{4\sec \theta} \\
&= \int \sec\theta\,d\theta.\end{align*}

To solve this integral we substitute

\begin{align*}u=\sec \theta +\tan \theta, \quad du = (\tan \theta+\sec\theta)\sec\theta\,d\theta,\end{align*}

and obtain

\begin{align*}
\int \sec\theta\,d\theta &= \int \frac{\sec \theta\,du}{(\tan\theta + \sec\theta)\sec \theta} \\
&= \int \frac{du}{u} = \ln|u| \\
&= \ln|\sec \theta + \tan \theta| + C.\end{align*}

We use the first substitution $\tan \theta = x/4$ to find that
$\cos \theta = \frac4{\sqrt{x^2+16}}$ so that our final answer becomes

\begin{align*}\int \frac{dx}{\sqrt{x^2+16}} = \ln\left|\frac{\sqrt{x^2+16}}4 + \frac{x}4\right| + C.\end{align*}

\emph{Note that $\ln\left|\frac{\sqrt{x^2+16}}4 + \frac{x}4\right| + C$
can also be written as $\sinh^{-1}\left(\frac{x}4\right) +C,$ the
inverse hyperbolic sine function.}
